'''Sagittarius A*''', abbreviated '''Sgr&nbsp;A*''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|s|æ|dʒ|_|ˈ|eɪ|_|s|t|ɑːr}} {{Respell|SADGE|AY|star}}<ref>{{Cite web |title=Astronomers reveal first image of the black hole at the heart of our galaxy |url=https://eventhorizontelescope.org/blog/astronomers-reveal-first-image-black-hole-heart-our-galaxy |access-date=May 12, 2022 |website=Event Horizon Telescope |date=May 12, 2022 |language=en |archive-date=May 12, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220512132514/https://eventhorizontelescope.org/blog/astronomers-reveal-first-image-black-hole-heart-our-galaxy |url-status=live }}</ref>), is the [[supermassive black hole]]<ref>{{Cite news |last=Parsons |first=Jeff |date=October 31, 2018 |title=Scientists find proof a supermassive black hole is lurking at the centre of the Milky Way |language=en-GB |work=Metro |url=https://metro.co.uk/2018/10/31/scientists-find-proof-a-supermassive-black-hole-is-lurking-at-the-centre-of-the-milky-way-8092994/ |url-status=live |access-date=October 31, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181031214911/https://metro.co.uk/2018/10/31/scientists-find-proof-a-supermassive-black-hole-is-lurking-at-the-centre-of-the-milky-way-8092994/ |archive-date=October 31, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Mosher |first=Dave |date=October 31, 2018 |title=A 'mind-boggling' telescope observation has revealed the point of no return for our galaxy's monster black hole |work=The Middletown Press |publisher=Business Insider |url=https://www.middletownpress.com/technology/businessinsider/article/Supermassive-black-holes-gorge-themselves-on-a-7971243.php |url-status=dead |access-date=May 16, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181031144008/https://www.middletownpress.com/technology/businessinsider/article/Supermassive-black-holes-gorge-themselves-on-a-7971243.php |archive-date=October 31, 2018}}</ref><ref name="plait">{{cite web |last1=Plait |first1=Phil |author-link=Phil Plait |date=November 7, 2018 |title=Astronomers See Material Orbiting a Black Hole *Right* at the Edge of Forever |url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/astronomers-see-material-orbiting-a-black-hole-right-at-the-edge-of-forever |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181110143143/https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/astronomers-see-material-orbiting-a-black-hole-right-at-the-edge-of-forever |archive-date=10 November 2018 |access-date=November 12, 2018 |website=Bad Astronomy |publisher=Syfy Wire |language=en}}</ref> at the [[Galactic Center]] of the [[Milky Way]]. Viewed from Earth, it is located near the border of the constellations [[Sagittarius (constellation)|Sagittarius]] and [[Scorpius]], about 5.6° south of the [[ecliptic]],<ref>Calculated using [https://frostydrew.org/utilities.dc/convert/tool-eq_coordinates/pss-fdo/ Equatorial and Ecliptic Coordinates] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721134008/https://frostydrew.org/utilities.dc/convert/tool-eq_coordinates/pss-fdo/|date=July 21, 2019|title=}} calculator</ref> visually close to the [[Butterfly Cluster]] (M6) and [[Lambda Scorpii]].

The object is a bright and very compact [[astronomical radio source]]. The name Sagittarius A* distinguishes the compact source from the larger (and much brighter) [[Sagittarius&nbsp;A]] (Sgr&nbsp;A) region in which it is embedded.  Sgr&nbsp;A* was discovered in 1974 by {{ill|Bruce Balick|de}} and Robert L. Brown,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Balick |first1=B. |last2=Brown |first2=R. L.|title=Intense sub-arcsecond structure in the galactic center|journal=Astrophysical Journal|date=1 December 1974|volume=194|issue=1|pages=265–270|doi=10.1086/153242|bibcode=1974ApJ...194..265B|s2cid=121802758 |doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>[[#Melia|Melia 2007]], p. 7</ref> and the [[asterisk]] {{char|'''*'''}} was assigned in 1982 by Brown,<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Brown |first1=Robert L. |date=November 1, 1982 |title=Precessing Jets in Sagittarius A: Gas Dynamics in the Central Parsec of the Galaxy |journal=The Astrophysical Journal |volume=262 |pages=110&ndash;119 |bibcode=1982ApJ...262..110B |doi=10.1086/160401 |doi-access=free }}</ref> who understood that the strongest radio emission from the center of the galaxy appeared to be due to a compact non-thermal radio object.

The observations of several stars orbiting Sagittarius A*, particularly [[S2 (star)|star S2]], have been used to determine the mass and upper limits on the radius of the object. Based on mass and increasingly precise radius limits, astronomers have concluded that Sagittarius A* must be the central supermassive black hole of the Milky Way galaxy.<ref name="Henderson">{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/science/article5316001.ece|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081216235509/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/science/article5316001.ece|archive-date=2008-12-16|title=Astronomers confirm black hole at the heart of the Milky Way|last=Henderson|first=Mark|date=2009-12-09 |publisher= Times Online|access-date=2019-06-06}}</ref> The current value of its mass is 4.297{{±|0.012}} million [[solar mass]]es.<ref name="GRAVITY"/>

[[Reinhard Genzel]] and [[Andrea M. Ghez|Andrea Ghez]] were awarded the 2020 [[Nobel Prize in Physics]] for their discovery that Sagittarius A* is a supermassive compact object, for which a [[black hole]] was the only plausible explanation at the time.<ref>{{cite news|date=6 October 2020|title=The Nobel Prize in Physics 2020|language=en-us|url=https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/physics/2020/summary/|access-date=7 October 2020|archive-date=24 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210424115309/https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/physics/2020/summary/|url-status=live}}</ref>

In May 2022, astronomers released the first image of the [[accretion disk]] around the horizon of Sagittarius A*, confirming it to be a black hole, using the [[Event Horizon Telescope]], a world-wide network of radio observatories.<ref name="AJ-202205">{{cite journal |last=Bower |first=Geoffrey C. |date=May 2022 |title=Focus on First Sgr A* Results from the Event Horizon Telescope |url=https://iopscience.iop.org/journal/2041-8205/page/Focus_on_First_Sgr_A_Results |journal=[[The Astrophysical Journal]] |access-date=May 12, 2022 |archive-date=July 19, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220719162915/https://iopscience.iop.org/journal/2041-8205/page/Focus_on_First_Sgr_A_Results |url-status=live }}</ref> This is the second confirmed image of a black hole, after [[Messier 87#Supermassive black hole M87*|Messier 87's supermassive black hole]] in 2019.<ref name="ESO2208">{{cite news|url=https://www.eso.org/public/news/eso2208-eht-mw/|title=Astronomers reveal first image of the black hole at the heart of our galaxy|work=eso.org|date=12 May 2022|access-date=12 May 2022|archive-date=May 12, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220512130910/https://www.eso.org/public/news/eso2208-eht-mw/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="NYT-20220512"/> The black hole itself is not seen, only nearby objects whose behavior is influenced by the black hole. The observed radio and infrared energy emanates from gas and dust heated to millions of degrees while falling into the black hole.<ref name="DetectionOfBlackHoleSrgA" />

==Observation and description ==
[[File:Sagittarius Astar in the constellation of Sagittarius.tif|thumb|Sagittarius A* in the constellation of Sagittarius. The black hole is marked with a red circle within the constellation of Sagittarius (The Archer). This map shows most of the stars visible to the unaided eye under good conditions.]]
[[File:Eso2208-eht-mwe.tif|thumb|The diameter of Sagittarius A* is smaller than the orbit of [[Mercury (planet)|Mercury]].]]

On May 12, 2022, the first image of Sagittarius A* was released by the [[Event Horizon Telescope Collaboration]]. The image, which is based on radio interferometer data taken in 2017, confirms that the object contains a black hole. This is the second image of a black hole.<ref name="ESO2208"/><ref name="Shadow" /> This image took five years of calculations to process.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Hensley |first=Kerry |date=2022-05-12 |title=First Image of the Milky Way's Supermassive Black Hole |url=https://aasnova.org/2022/05/12/first-image-of-the-milky-ways-supermassive-black-hole/ |access-date=2022-05-13 |website=AAS Nova |language=en-US |archive-date=August 2, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220802102347/https://aasnova.org/2022/05/12/first-image-of-the-milky-ways-supermassive-black-hole/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The data were collected by eight radio observatories at six geographical sites. Radio images are produced from data by [[aperture synthesis]], usually from night-long observations of stable sources. The radio emission from Sgr A* varies on the order of minutes, complicating the analysis.<ref>{{cite journal |author=The Event Horizon Telescope Collaboration |date=1 May 2022 |title=First Sagittarius A* Event Horizon Telescope Results. III. Imaging of the Galactic Center Supermassive Black Hole |journal=The Astrophysical Journal Letters |volume=930 |issue=2 |page=L14 |arxiv=2311.09479 |bibcode=2022ApJ...930L..14E |doi=10.3847/2041-8213/ac6429 |issn=2041-8205 |eissn=2041-8213 |s2cid=248744704 |doi-access=free}}</ref>

Their result gives an overall [[angular diameter|angular size]] for the source of {{val|51.8|2.3|ul=μas}}.<ref name="Shadow">{{cite journal |author=The Event Horizon Telescope Collaboration |date=1 May 2022 |title=First Sagittarius A* Event Horizon Telescope Results. I. The Shadow of the Supermassive Black Hole in the Center of the Milky Way |journal=The Astrophysical Journal Letters |volume=930 |issue=2 |page=L12 |bibcode=2022ApJ...930L..12E |doi=10.3847/2041-8213/ac6674 |issn=2041-8205 |eissn=2041-8213 |s2cid=248744791 |doi-access=free |hdl-access=free |hdl=10261/278882}}</ref> At a distance of {{Convert|26,000|ly|pc|lk=on|abbr=off}}, this yields a diameter of {{Convert|51.8|e6km|e6mi|abbr=none}}.{{efn|name=dc1|This roughly equates to around 37 times the diameter of the Sun at ~1,400,000 kilometers (~865,000 miles).}} For comparison, Earth is {{Convert|150|e6km|AU e6mi|lk=on|abbr=none}} from the [[Sun]], and [[Mercury (planet)|Mercury]] is {{Convert|46|e6km|AU e6mi|abbr=unit}} from the Sun at [[Apsis|perihelion]]. The [[proper motion]] of Sgr&nbsp;A* is approximately −2.70&nbsp;[[Minute and second of arc|mas]] per year for the [[right ascension]] and −5.6&nbsp;mas per year for the [[declination]].<ref>[[#Backer|Backer and Sramek 1999]], § 3</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://iopscience.iop.org/journal/2041-8205/page/Focus_on_EHT|title=Focus on the First Event Horizon Telescope Results – The Astrophysical Journal Letters – IOPscience|website=iopscience.iop.org|access-date=2019-04-10|archive-date=2019-05-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514171744/https://iopscience.iop.org/journal/2041-8205/page/Focus_on_EHT|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/10/science/black-hole-picture.html|title=Black Hole Picture Revealed for the First Time|last=Overbye|first=Dennis|date=2019-04-10|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-04-10|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-date=2019-05-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190521020231/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/10/science/black-hole-picture.html|url-status=live}}</ref>
The telescope's measurement of these black holes tested Einstein's [[theory of relativity]] more rigorously than has previously been done, and the results match perfectly.<ref name="NYT-20220512">{{Cite news |last=Overbye |first=Dennis |date=2022-05-12 |title=The Milky Way's Black Hole Comes to Light |language=en-US |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2022/05/12/science/black-hole-photo.html |access-date=2022-05-12 |issn=0362-4331 |archive-date=May 12, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220512040455/https://www.nytimes.com/2022/05/12/science/black-hole-photo.html/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In 2019, measurements made with the High-resolution Airborne Wideband Camera-Plus (HAWC+) mounted in the [[Stratospheric Observatory for Infrared Astronomy|SOFIA]] aircraft<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sofia.usra.edu/science/instruments/hawc#|title=HAWC+, the Far-Infrared Camera and Polarimeter for SOFIA|date=2018|access-date=2021-08-03|archive-date=2021-08-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210803210336/https://www.sofia.usra.edu/science/instruments/hawc|url-status=live}}</ref> revealed that magnetic fields cause the surrounding ring of gas and dust, temperatures of which range from {{Convert|-280|to|17500|F|K C}},<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.space.com/milky-way-monster-black-hole-cool-disk.html|title=The Milky Way's Monster Black Hole Has a Cool Gas Halo – Literally|work=Space.com|date=5 June 2019|access-date=19 June 2019|archive-date=19 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190619004814/https://www.space.com/milky-way-monster-black-hole-cool-disk.html|url-status=live}}</ref> to flow into an orbit around Sagittarius A*, keeping black hole emissions low.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.space.com/milky-way-supermassive-black-hole-magnetic-field-quiet.html|title=Magnetic Fields May Muzzle Milky Way's Monster Black Hole|work=Space.com|date=14 June 2019|access-date=19 June 2019|archive-date=18 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190618050808/https://www.space.com/milky-way-supermassive-black-hole-magnetic-field-quiet.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

Astronomers have been unable to observe Sgr&nbsp;A* in the [[Visible spectrum|optical spectrum]] because of the effect of 25 [[Magnitude (astronomy)|magnitudes]] of [[Extinction (astronomy)|extinction]] by dust and gas between the source and Earth.<ref name="Osterbrock">[[#Osterbrock|Osterbrock and Ferland 2006]], p. 390</ref>

==History==
In April 1933, [[Karl Guthe Jansky|Karl Jansky]], considered one of the fathers of radio astronomy, discovered that a radio signal was coming from a location in the direction of the constellation of Sagittarius, towards the center of the Milky Way.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://armaghplanet.com/karl-jansky-the-father-of-radio-astronomy.html |title=Karl Jansky: The Father of Radio Astronomy |date=29 August 2012 |access-date=2019-01-27 |archive-date=2019-06-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190628163259/http://www.armaghplanet.com/karl-jansky-the-father-of-radio-astronomy.html |url-status=live }}</ref> The radio source later became known as [[Sagittarius A]]. His observations did not extend quite as far south as we now know to be the Galactic Center.<ref name="goss_history">{{cite journal |last1=Goss |first1=W. M. |last2=McGee |first2=R. X. |title=The Discovery of the Radio Source Sagittarius A (Sgr A) |journal=The Galactic Center, Astronomical Society of the Pacific Conference Series |date=1996 |volume=102 |pages=369 |bibcode=1996ASPC..102..369G |url=https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1996ASPC..102..369G/abstract |access-date=25 February 2021 |archive-date=3 March 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210303171739/https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1996ASPC..102..369G/abstract |url-status=live }}</ref> Observations by [[Jack Piddington]] and [[Harry Clive Minnett|Harry Minnett]] using the [[CSIRO]] radio telescope at [[Potts Hill Reservoirs 1 and 2|Potts Hill Reservoir]], in [[Sydney]] discovered a discrete and bright "Sagittarius-Scorpius" radio source,<ref name="piddington">{{cite journal |last1=Piddington |first1=J. H. |last2=Minnett |first2=H. C. |title=Observations of Galactic Radiation at Frequencies of 1200 and 3000 Mc/s. |journal=Australian Journal of Scientific Research A |date=1 December 1951 |volume=4 |issue=4 |pages=459 |doi=10.1071/CH9510459 |bibcode=1951AuSRA...4..459P |url=https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1951AuSRA...4..459P/abstract |access-date=25 February 2021 |archive-date=13 April 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210413090955/https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1951AuSRA...4..459P/abstract |url-status=live }}</ref> which after further observation with the {{Convert|80|ft|m|abbr=off|adj=on}} CSIRO radio telescope at [[Dover Heights]] was identified in a letter to ''[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]'' as the probable Galactic Center.<ref name="galactic_centre_mcgee">{{cite journal |last1=McGee |first1=R. X. |last2=Bolton |first2=J. G. |title=Probable observation of the galactic nucleus at 400 Mc./s. |journal=Nature |date=1 May 1954 |volume=173 |issue=4412 |pages=985–987 |doi=10.1038/173985b0 |bibcode=1954Natur.173..985M |s2cid=4188235 |url=https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1954Natur.173..985M/abstract |access-date=25 February 2021 |issn=0028-0836 |archive-date=30 January 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220130113909/https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1954Natur.173..985M/abstract |url-status=live }}</ref>

Later observations showed that Sagittarius A actually consists of several overlapping sub-components; a bright and very compact component, Sgr&nbsp;A*, was discovered on February 13 and 15, 1974, by Balick and Robert L Brown using the baseline interferometer of the [[National Radio Astronomy Observatory]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Balick |first1=B. |last2=Brown |first2=R. L.|title=Intense sub-arcsecond structure in the galactic center|journal=Astrophysical Journal|date=1 December 1974|volume=194|issue=1|pages=265–270|doi=10.1086/153242|bibcode=1974ApJ...194..265B|s2cid=121802758 |doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>[[#Melia|Melia 2007]], p. 7</ref> The name Sgr&nbsp;A* was coined by Brown in a 1982 paper because the radio source was "exciting", and [[excited state]]s of atoms are denoted with asterisks.<ref>{{Cite journal|arxiv=astro-ph/0305074 |title=The Discovery of Sgr&nbsp;A* |journal=Astronomische Nachrichten |volume=324 |issue=1 |page=497 |date=2003-05-06 |last1=Goss |first1=W. M. |last2=Brown |first2=Robert L. |last3=Lo |first3=K. Y. |doi=10.1002/asna.200385047 |bibcode=2003ANS...324..497G }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Precessing jets in Sagittarius A – Gas dynamics in the central parsec of the galaxy|first=R. L. |last=Brown |journal=Astrophysical Journal, Part 1 |volume=262 |date=1982-11-01 |pages=110–119 |bibcode=1982ApJ...262..110B|doi=10.1086/160401 |doi-access=free }}</ref>

Since the 1980s, it has been evident that the central component of Sgr A* is likely a black hole. In 1994, infrared and sub-millimetre spectroscopy studies by a [[University of California, Berkeley|Berkeley]] team involving [[Nobel Prize in Physics|Nobel Laureate]] [[Charles H. Townes]] and future Nobel Prize Winner [[Reinhard Genzel]] showed that the mass of Sgr A* was tightly concentrated and on the order of 3 million Suns.<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Genzel|first1=R|last2=Hollenbach|first2=D|last3=Townes|first3=C H|date=1994 |title=The nucleus of our Galaxy|journal=Reports on Progress in Physics|volume=57|issue=5|pages=417–479|doi=10.1088/0034-4885/57/5/001|issn=0034-4885|bibcode=1994RPPh...57..417G|s2cid=250900662}}</ref>

On October 16, 2002, an international team led by [[Reinhard Genzel]] at the [[Max Planck Institute for Extraterrestrial Physics]] reported the observation of the motion of the star [[S2 (star)|S2]] near Sagittarius A* throughout a period of ten years. According to the team's analysis, the data ruled out the possibility that Sgr A* contains a cluster of dark stellar objects or a mass of [[Degenerate matter|degenerate fermions]], strengthening the evidence for a massive black hole. The observations of S2 used [[near-infrared]] (NIR) [[Astronomical interferometer|interferometry]] (in the Ks-band, i.e. 2.1&nbsp;[[μm]]) because of reduced [[Extinction (astronomy)|interstellar extinction]] in this band. SiO [[Astrophysical maser|maser]]s were used to align NIR images with radio observations, as they can be observed in both NIR and radio bands. The rapid motion of S2 (and other nearby stars) easily stood out against slower-moving stars along the line-of-sight so these could be subtracted from the images.<ref>[[#Schodel|Schödel ''et al.'' 2002]]</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Sakai |first1=Shoko |last2=Lu |first2=Jessica R. |last3=Ghez |first3=Andrea |last4=Jia |first4=Siyao |last5=Do |first5=Tuan |last6=Witzel |first6=Gunther |last7=Gautam |first7=Abhimat K. |last8=Hees |first8=Aurelien |last9=Becklin |first9=E. |last10=Matthews |first10=K. |last11=Hosek |first11=M. W. |date=2019-03-05 |title=The Galactic Center: An Improved Astrometric Reference Frame for Stellar Orbits around the Supermassive Black Hole |journal=The Astrophysical Journal |language=en |volume=873 |issue=1 |pages=65 |doi=10.3847/1538-4357/ab0361 |arxiv=1901.08685 |bibcode=2019ApJ...873...65S |s2cid=119331998 |issn=1538-4357 |doi-access=free }}</ref>

[[File:Dusty cloud G2 passes the supermassive black hole at the centre of the Milky Way.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Dusty cloud G2 passes the supermassive black hole at the center of the Milky Way.<ref>{{cite web|title=Best View Yet of Dusty Cloud Passing Galactic Centre Black Hole|url=http://www.eso.org/public/news/eso1512/|access-date=16 June 2015|archive-date=7 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150407034121/http://www.eso.org/public/news/eso1512/|url-status=live}}</ref>]]
The VLBI radio observations of Sagittarius A* could also be aligned centrally with the NIR images, so the focus of S2's elliptical orbit was found to coincide with the position of Sagittarius A*. From examining the [[Kepler orbit|Keplerian orbit]] of S2, they determined the mass of Sagittarius A* to be {{val|4.1|0.6|u=million}} [[solar mass]]es, confined in a volume with a radius no more than 17 light-hours ({{Convert|120|AU|e9km e9mi|lk=on|abbr=unit|disp=sqbr}}).<ref>[[#Ghez03|Ghez ''et al.'' (2003) "The First Measurement of Spectral Lines in a Short-Period Star Bound to the Galaxy's Central Black Hole: A Paradox of Youth" Astrophysical Journal '''586''' L127]]</ref> Later observations of the star S14 showed the mass of the object to be about 4.1&nbsp;million solar masses within a volume with radius no larger than 6.25 light-hours ({{Convert|45|AU|e9km e9mi|abbr=unit|disp=sqbr}}).<ref name="Ghez08">{{cite journal | last = Ghez | first = A. M. | display-authors=etal | title = Measuring Distance and Properties of the Milky Way's Central Supermassive Black Hole with Stellar Orbits | journal = Astrophysical Journal | date = December 2008 | volume = 689 | issue = 2 | pages = 1044–1062 | arxiv=0808.2870 | bibcode = 2008ApJ...689.1044G | doi = 10.1086/592738| s2cid = 18335611 }}</ref> S175 passed within a similar distance.<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Gillessen|first1=S.|last2=Plewa|first2=P. M.|last3=Eisenhauer|first3=F.|last4=Sari|first4=R.|last5=Waisberg|first5=I.|last6=Habibi|first6=M.|last7=Pfuhl|first7=O.|last8=George|first8=E.|last9=Dexter|first9=J.|date=2017|title=An Update on Monitoring Stellar Orbits in the Galactic Center|journal=The Astrophysical Journal|language=en|volume=837|issue=1|page=30|doi=10.3847/1538-4357/aa5c41|issn=0004-637X|arxiv=1611.09144|bibcode=2017ApJ...837...30G|s2cid=119087402 |doi-access=free }}</ref> For comparison, the [[Schwarzschild radius]] is {{Convert|0.08|AU|e6km e6mi|abbr=unit}}. They also determined the distance from Earth to the [[Galactic Center]] (the rotational center of the Milky Way), which is important in calibrating astronomical distance scales, as {{Convert|8,000|±|600|lk=on|abbr=off|pc|ly|sigfig=1}}. In November 2004, a team of astronomers reported the discovery of a potential [[intermediate-mass black hole]], referred to as [[GCIRS 13E]], orbiting 3 light-years from Sagittarius A*. This black hole of 1,300 solar masses is within a cluster of seven stars. This observation may add support to the idea that supermassive black holes grow by absorbing nearby smaller black holes and stars.{{citation needed|date=May 2022}}

After monitoring stellar orbits around Sagittarius A* for 16 years, Gillessen ''et al.'' estimated the object's mass at {{val|4.31|0.38|u=million}} solar masses. The result was announced in 2008 and published in ''[[The Astrophysical Journal]]'' in 2009.<ref name="Gillessen">[[#Gillessen|Gillessen ''et al.'' 2009]]</ref> [[Reinhard Genzel]], team leader of the research, said the study has delivered "what is now considered to be the best empirical evidence that supermassive black holes do really exist. The stellar orbits in the Galactic Center show that the central mass concentration of four million solar masses must be a black hole, beyond any reasonable doubt."<ref>[[#ONeill|O'Neill 2008]]</ref>

On January 5, 2015, NASA reported observing an [[X-ray]] flare 400 times brighter than usual, a record-breaker, from Sgr&nbsp;A*. The unusual event may have been caused by the breaking apart of an [[asteroid]] falling into the black hole or by the entanglement of [[magnetic field]] lines within gas flowing into Sgr&nbsp;A*, according to astronomers.<ref name="NASA-20150105">{{cite web |last1=Chou |first1=Felicia |last2=Anderson |first2=Janet |last3=Watzke |first3=Megan |title=NASA's Chandra Detects Record-Breaking Outburst from Milky Way's Black Hole |url=http://www.nasa.gov/press/2015/january/nasa-s-chandra-detects-record-breaking-outburst-from-milky-way-s-black-hole/ |date=January 5, 2015 |publisher=[[NASA]] |access-date=January 6, 2015 |archive-date=January 6, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150106100532/http://www.nasa.gov/press/2015/january/nasa-s-chandra-detects-record-breaking-outburst-from-milky-way-s-black-hole/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 13 May 2019, astronomers using the [[Keck Observatory]] witnessed a sudden brightening of Sgr&nbsp;A*, which became 75 times brighter than usual, suggesting that the supermassive black hole may have encountered another object.<ref>{{cite news |title=Our Galaxy's Supermassive Black Hole Has Emitted a Mysteriously Bright Flare |url=https://www.sciencealert.com/our-galaxy-s-supermassive-black-hole-just-mysteriously-got-really-really-bright |date=12 August 2019 |work=Science Alert |access-date=12 August 2019 |archive-date=12 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190812120201/https://www.sciencealert.com/our-galaxy-s-supermassive-black-hole-just-mysteriously-got-really-really-bright |url-status=live }}</ref>

In June 2023, unexplained filaments of [[Radio wave|radio]] energy were found associated with Sagittarius A*.<ref name="NYT-20230608">{{cite news |last=Overbye |first=Dennis |authorlink=Dennis Overbye |title=Our Local Black Hole Serves Up an 'Awe Moment' – Filaments of radio energy from Sagittarius A*, the black hole at the center of the Milky Way galaxy, are turning astronomers' heads. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2023/06/08/science/astronomy-cosmos-black-hole.html |date=8 June 2023 |work=[[The New York Times]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20230608155337/https://www.nytimes.com/2023/06/08/science/astronomy-cosmos-black-hole.html |archivedate=8 June 2023 |accessdate=9 June 2023 }}</ref>

